Today, June 8th we will have a modified Promotion celebration.
Families can drive through the MS bus lane between 6-8pm. Only the 8th grade student will be able to exit the car. Students will pick up their certificate and get a photo. Photos will be email/mailed home. We are excited to see the students and look forward to our ‘modified’ promotion.

CONGRATULATIONS TO OUR 8TH GRADERS!!!!!
CLASS OF 2024

Las familias pueden conducir a través del carril de autobuses de la secundaria entre las 6 y las 8 p.m. Solo el estudiante de octavo grado podrá salir del auto. Los estudiantes recogerán su certificado y obtendrán una foto. Las fotos serán enviadas por correo electrónico a casa o a domicilio. Estamos emocionados de ver a los estudiantes y esperamos con entusiasmo nuestra promoción "modificada".

¡FELICIDADES A NUESTROS ESTUDIANTES DE 8º GRADO!
CLASE DE 2024

MEAL SCHEDULE UPDATE | ACTUALIZACIÓN DEL PROGRAMA DE COMIDAS

In an effort to limit exposure, effective Thursday, March 26, we will have one meal pickup and delivery per day. Afternoon schedule remains the same: Elementary: 11:30 – 12:30 pm; Delivery: 11:00 – 11:30. This meal pickup and delivery will include both breakfast and lunch.

En un esfuerzo por limitar la exposición, a partir del jueves 26 de marzo, tendremos una entrega de comida por día. El horario de la tarde sigue siendo el mismo: La primaria: 11:30 - 12:30 pm; Entrega en bus: 11:00 - 11:30. Esta entrega de comida incluirá desayuno y almuerzo.

shared_text:
Douglas County Sheriff's Office - Washington
May 10, 2019 at 12:08 AM ·

This week the Douglas County Sheriff’s Office participated in National Bike to School Day Events in Waterville and Bridgeport. Yesterday, Sargent Poppie and Deputy Morley helped young Waterville bikers fit their helmets, distributed bike locks and safety devices, provided helmets to those who didn’t have one, and taught the kids about road safety. And today Deputy Tonseth was able to provide these same wonderful services to children in Bridgeport! This event could not have happened without all of the hard work and dedication of Traffic Safety Coordinator, Eveline Roy. Eveline applied for the grant and followed the process through that made it possible to help these young people throughout our County. Thank you so much to Eveline and our DCSO staff!

post_text:
Wow! If you see them please congratulate them!

Senior Oscar Gomez took 2nd Place in photography at the regional art show in Wenatchee with his picture titled "Watch Out, She's Coming!". His picture was also selected "Best-in-Show" work, which means it will go to the State Art Show in Olympia.

Alondra Jimenez took 3rd Place in photography with her picture titled "Feather Sunset".

"This is the 2nd year in a row that Bridgeport students have taken two of the three awards in Photography, and the second year one of the those works had advanced to state. Not bad, considering we're up against all high schools from Cashmere north to the border, I'm pretty proud of our kids work!"~Brad Skiff

Construction Update:
During the cold and snow, construction has been focused on the gym. The ceiling has been removed and the stage area has been stripped out. The girl’s locker room has been removed and prepped for new construction. The concrete cutters removed more of the foundation concrete so new plumbing can be put in place. The gym bleachers are being removed and will be put into use for softball and baseball.

Scott Sattler, Superintendent

post_text:
Washington State 2018 Healthy Youth Survey

Our district is participating in the Washington State 2018 Healthy Youth Survey during Fall 2018.

The Healthy Youth Survey includes questions related to physical activity and diet, unintentional and intentional injury, substance use, risk and protective factors, access to school-based services, and sexual behaviors, abuse and orientation. Survey results are used by schools, communitites and state agencies to plan programs to support our youth and reduce their risks.

The healthy Youth Survey is given to students in grades 6, 8, 10 and 12 across Washington State.

Student Participation is completely voluntary and anonymous.

Any questions please call the District Office at 509-686-5656.
